ignoring) a problem in a series of case studies that range from strategic decisions in World War I and the Korean War to the wars in Vietnam and Iraq. Too often, unexamined premises color initial decisions to pursue a policy and shape the strategies leaders employ to achieve their goals, with grave consequences for their countries, organizations, and potentially the world. Timely and important, Prisoners of Their Premises demonstrates the real costs leaders incur by failing to question their assumptions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aInternational relationsxDecision makingvCase studies. 0aInternational relationsxDecision making. 0aPolitical sciencexDecision makingvCase studies. 0aPolitical sciencexDecision making. 0aPolitics and warzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  adecision making, politicians, critical thinking, vietnam, assumptions, strategy, war, iraq, korea, ww1, leaders, leadership, rationality, confirmation bias, information, dissonance, harry truman, soviet union, foreign relations, diplomacy, power, international, china, aggression, invasion, attack, communism, macarthur, threat, intervention.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226822815423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226822815/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles